size(100);
currentprojection = orthographic(25,150,100);
triple A = (1,1,0), B = (2,1,0), C = (2,2,0), D = (1,2,0), O = (1.5,1,0);
triple E1 = (1,1,4/3), F1 = (2,1,4/3), G1 = (2,2,4/3), H1 = (1,2,4/3);
triple E2 = (-1,-1,4/3), F2 = (-2,-1,4/3), G2 = (-2,-2,4/3), H2 = (-1,-2,4/3);
triple I1 = (1,1,-4/3), J1 = (2,1,-4/3), K1 = (2,2,-4/3), L1 = (1,2,-4/3);
triple I2 = (-1,-1,-4/3), J2 = (-2,-1,-4/3), K2 = (-2,-2,-4/3), L2 = (-1,-2,-4/3);
triple M = (1,1,0);

draw(A--B--G1--H1--cycle);
draw(A--C--E1--F1--cycle);
draw(B--E1);
draw(C--F1);
draw(D--G1);
draw(D--H1);
draw(O--E1);
draw(O--F1);
draw(A--E1);
draw(B--F1);
draw(C--G1);
draw(D--H1);
triple K = barycenter({A,B,C,D,M});
draw(K--M,linetype("8 8"));
[/asy] For each vertex, we can draw a diagonal to each other vertex except itself and the two vertices that are directly connected to it by an edge. Therefore, for each vertex, there are $n-3$ possible diagonals, where $n$ is the number of vertices. Considering all vertices, this gives a preliminary count of $n(n - 3)$ diagonals. However, this count includes each diagonal twice (once from each of its endpoints), so the actual number of diagonals is half of this preliminary count. To adjust for this, we divide by 2, resulting in $D = \frac{n(n - 3)}{2}$ diagonals. In this case, we have $n = 10$ vertices. Plugging this into our formula, we get $D = \frac{10(10 - 3)}{2} = \frac{70}{2} = 35$ diagonals. Thus, a pentagonal prism has \boxed{35} diagonals. [/think]

